re</gtr:otherNames><gtr:surname>Mitton</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-173-27-0017"><gtr:id>CDC25BD4-C849-4155-97CD-FA293EF1F70A</gtr:id><gtr:title>Fraud and Error: Factors Affecting Compliance with rules</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-173-27-0017</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>Social security benefit non-compliance ranges from deliberate fraud to innocent error. Examples include not declaring income or savings, feigning or exaggerating illness or disability, identity fraud and claiming as a single person while living with a partner. This project is a review of literature and evidence to increase understanding of this policy area.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />Existing research suggests the effect on compliance of the following should be explored:
&lt;br />
&lt;ul>
 &lt;li>Benefit design ? eg the ease with which rules can be complied with.&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Deterrence ? eg sanctions and risk of detection.&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Social context and beliefs ? eg perceived fairness of benefits system, perceived social norms of compliance linked to guilt and shame.&lt;/li>
 &lt;li>Opportunity ? eg for cash in hand work within the social network.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul>
&lt;br />The researcher will also look at lessons from other systems requiring active compliance with their rules. For example, there is a very large economic and psychological literature on tax compliance. The other areas the researcher will look at include TV licensing, insurance, child support payments, workplace fiddling, VAT, and National Insurance.
&lt;br />
&lt;br />The output will be a report which will feed into policy, as well as identifying future research needs.
&lt;br />
